areer transition, he went on more than 150 informational interviews and later interviewed twelve other professionals who had left higher education for diverse fields. Drawing on everything he learned, Caterine helps readers chart their own course to a rewarding new career. He addresses dozens of key issues, including overcoming psychological difficulties, translating academic experience for nonacademics, and meeting the challenges of a first job in a new field.Providing clear, concrete ways to move forward at each stage of your career change, even when the going gets tough, Leaving Academia is both realistic and filled with hope.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCareer changes-Handbooks, manuals, etc. 7aEDUCATION / Counseling / Career Development.2bisacsh  aAcademic degree.  aAcademic tenure.  aAccounting.  aAction item.  aAdage.  aAnd Interest.  aAnecdote.  aAssistant professor.  aBlog.  aCalculation.  aCareer.  aCase study.  aClassroom.  aCompetitive landscape.  aConsideration.  aConsultant.  aConsulting firm.  aCover letter.  aCriticism.  aCubicle.  aCurriculum vitae.  aDebt.  aDetermination.  aDiscernment.  aDoctor of Philosophy.  aDoctorate.  aElevator pitch.  aEmail.  aEmployment.  aEntry-level job.  aExecutive director.  aExpense.  aExpert.  aExplanation.  aFast Company (magazine).  aFinding.  aFollow-up.  aFunding.  aGraduate school.  aHealth insurance.  aIncome.  aIndication (medicine).  aInformational interview.  aInternship.  aInterview.  aJob fair.  aJob interview.  aJournalism.  aLearning.  aLecture.  aLinkedIn.  aMarketing.  aMeeting.  aMonograph.  aNarrative.  aOpportunity cost.  aOptimism.  aOrganization.  aOverqualification.  aPeer review.  aPersonal branding.  aPhilosopher.  a